{{Infobox airline | airline = Air Alsace | image = | image_size = | alt = | IATA = | ICAO = | callsign = | founded = | commenced = 1962 | ceased = 1981 | aoc = | bases = [[Colmar Airport|Colmar-Houssen Aerodrome]] | hubs = | secondary_hubs = | focus_cities = | frequent_flyer = | lounge = | alliance = | subsidiaries = | fleet_size = | destinations = | company_slogan = | parent = | headquarters = [[Colmar]], [[France]] | key_people = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | profit = | assets = | equity = | website = }}
[[Image:AirAlsace.jpg|right|250px|thumb|Company Logo]]
'''Société Air Alsace''' was an airline with its head office on the grounds of the [[Colmar Airport|Colmar-Houssen Aerodrome]] in [[Colmar]], [[France]].<ref>"World Airline Directory." ''[[Flight International]]''. 13 February 1975. [http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1975/1975%20-%200295.html?search=%22Air%20Alsace%22 247].</ref>
==Company history== [[Image:VFW-614 Air Alsace Basle - 15 Oct 1977.jpg|thumb|right| VFW 614 of Air Alsace]] [[Image:SN601 Corvette F-BVPE Alsace BRU 12.09.77 edited-3.jpg|thumb|right|Aerospatiale Corvette of Air Alsace at Brussels Airport in 1977 wearing the titles of Air France]] Air Alsace began as an [[air taxi]] operation based in [[Colmar]] in 1962. It commenced operations using small aircraft. From 1974 it began to operate scheduled passenger [[regional airline|regional services]].
In cooperation with [[Air France]] it offered services to [[Amsterdam]], [[Brussels]], [[Cologne]], [[Rome]] and [[Strasbourg]]. Flights to London [[Gatwick]] and [[Milan]] were later added. Air Alsace entered the jet age in April 1976 with the delivery of their first [[VFW 614]] and it later acquired the [[Aerospatiale Corvette]] and the [[Fokker F.28 Fellowship]]. In 1981 the airline merged with [[TAT - Touraine Air Transport]] and [[Air Alpes]] to form [[TAT-Transport Aerien Transregional]].
